The house from the bones fascinates even after 100 years. Look into the interiors from Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of the ancient lake, the staircase resembles the spine of the dinosaur, and the balconies are open fish mouth.
This is the house of Casa Batlló in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
From the locals, thanks to its organic shapes, the house has earned the nickname House from the bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, facades resembling scales and omnipresent soft curves, all this is typical of Antoni Gaudí’s Art Nouveau.
The front of the house is played by dream lines, tender colors and textures resembling nature and animals.
In detailed observation, geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order are seen.
At night the whole facade of the house sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the shine of colors is even strengthened.
The winding and twisting of shapes appear equally in the interiors.
The wood in the waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of the door, cuckoo and rails.
The house of Batlló, located in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was built by the reconstruction of the house from 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, a wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on destroying the old building and building a completely new one, but soon adopted Gaudí’s idea for an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
The house of Casa Batlló, however, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was on his design board that decorations were created for the representative apartment of the property owner and the use of mosaic on the facade.
Many other artists and artists worked on the facade.
Working together on the designs of the Casa Batlló house started the successful cooperation of Jujola with Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Gaudí house Casa Milá and the Güell Park, where there are other Gaudí works.
From the locals, the house soon after it was completed earned thanks to its organic shapes the nickname ‘Bone House’.
Others called it a “living house” because of a specific window opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia, is likened at the top of the building.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí in the house designed for his time a unique system of central heating with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Bizarre may seem their forty-five degree inclination.
During the creation of Gaudí, he did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the building, however, it was so vague that two years later, the city council was threatened and asked for a correction.
For example, the council was interested in the fact that the building interfered with the pillars and the public walkway.
There has never been a remedy, on the contrary: only 15 days after the challenge of the city part, Josep Batlló requested (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social living room and on the third floor of the bedroom and private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented jewelry.
The entire six-storey house crosses the staircase, which can be climb up to the roof terrace itself.
The fundamental elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and direct lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The social part can be connected completely by opening the living room doors, and the larger company can communicate comfortably together without maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new facade, the house with Gaudí also acquired an unconventional roofing and two additional floors.
Gaudí's play with light, blue and white glazed tiles is impressive, which is covered with inner courtyards and skylights.
The game of two colors gives maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs the sun's rays on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló house, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most lavish apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the 100th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
The tours continued because they found it to be a very advantageous enterprise and in addition, they expanded the tours with common and attic spaces, including the roof terraces.
The entrance to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and the students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20% discount.
The sum greatly exceeds the entry price for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
