Longer pointer than ring indicates lower risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than the ring are at less risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is a surprising conclusion of a study published by the British Cancer Magazine on Wednesday.
It may be related to testosterone hormone levels.
“Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men under the age of 60,” study co-author Ros Eeles, professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick, said in a statement.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, especially in combination with genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and more than 3,000 healthy men were followed by colleagues in the UK.
More than half of the participants had a pointer on their right hand shorter than the ring.
They were given the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were as long.
In the case of those who had a marker longer than the ring, however, this risk fell by 33 percent, for men to sixty, the decrease was even 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed in the prenatal period - appears to reflect the different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer indicator.
Previous research has shown that testosterone just promotes growing prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, said that he knows about this study in a consistent manner, but he does not seem to know that the relationship between finger length and cancer is “fully proven”
