The United States is changing the rules for issuing visas
People will have to contact the Service Centres for visa applicants before they interview at the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011, the process of discussing visas to the Embassy of the United States and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Service Centres for Visa Applicants (shortly from English ASC) before interviewing the Consular Department.
Staff from the ASC shall collect biometric information from the applicant and they shall be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain benefits, including the following:
The total cost of completing the visa will be lower, there will no longer be a need to pay a fee for the meeting, the second for the processing of the application and another for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee which shall cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the amount equivalent to $140 for tourist visas, $150 for visa applications (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for business and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa won’t have to interview a consular official, but they will only turn to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Since biometric information will be collected at ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with the Consular Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Similarly, those who will apply for a visa at consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra fee for the service of $26.
For more information about the new visa application procedure, visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
