World Lighting Recovery Plan
The United Nations has proposed a plan in Cancún to restore home lighting, lighting stores and industrial spaces in 100 countries to achieve a GES reduction, which corresponds to nearly one-third of the further constraints to be achieved to stabilize the climate of the planet from now to 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the United Nations wants to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of difficult-to-implementable reduction commitments on the part of industrialised countries.
According to yesterday's plan, if the light bulbs that monopolize 50 to 70 percent of the market replace fluocompact bulbs or, even better, the bulbs with electroluminescent LEDs (DEL or -LED - in English), the essential amount of 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet formed due to lighting would be degraded.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of the world’s emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from the car park on the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should allow a decrease in global GES emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will need to be deducted from this balance of 5 Gts to achieve the stabilization of climate warming to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to avoid being out of control.
In hot bulbs, 95% of the energy is dispersed in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is a product of light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new bulbs with DEL, we reduce this consumption by twice.
Fluocompact bulbs last from 6000 to 10,000 hours on average.
The new light bulbs with DEL, such as the one that put into production this week Philips - this company was reportedly involved in a UN study - have an estimated lifetime of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a hot bulb, giving us an idea of possible savings with a refund plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
All of these new light bulbs can also work with reostats and emit less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers set up collectors.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluocompact bulb, but rather a heat-fired coal power plant that releases many mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, these centres put into circulation 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report also details the profits that each country would make from this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion a year for buying electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2 equivalent to 3.5 heat plants, the construction of which would cost 2.5 billion.
