The EU announces that in 2010 it released €2.2 billion, bringing it on the right track to comply with its promise of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are new and additional to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without prejudice to public aid for development.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus in what “new and additional” means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million to the three-year fast start funding title.
